# C++ String API Conventions

Apply these conventions when editing C++ interfaces and call sites.

## Rules

- Prefer `std::string_view` for read-only string inputs when ownership is not required and null termination is not required.
- Prefer `std::string&&` for true sink parameters (callee unconditionally stores/owns the string). Move into storage with `std::move`.
- Use `const std::string&` when integrating with downstream APIs that already require string-reference semantics.
- Use `const char*` at C API / null-terminated boundaries where ownership is not needed.
- For string-keyed unordered maps in addon code, prefer `TransparentStringMap` to enable heterogeneous lookup without temporary key allocation.

## Review checklist

- Is any read-only `const std::string&` parameter better as `std::string_view`?
- Is any sink currently modeled as `const std::string&` + copy instead of `std::string&&` + move?
- Does any `std::string_view` cross a boundary that requires `const std::string&` or `const char*`?
  - If yes, expose the stricter requirement at the right interface layer to avoid hidden redundant conversions.
- Is any `view.data()` passed to C APIs without guaranteed null termination?
- Is any map lookup constructing `std::string{view}` unnecessarily where transparent lookup is available?

## Quick examples

```cpp
// GOOD: read-only
bool hasModel(std::string_view id);

// GOOD: sink
void setModelId(std::string&& id) { modelId_ = std::move(id); }

// AVOID: hidden temporary for map lookup
auto it = counts.find(std::string{keyView});
```

